159
00:07:30,551 --> 00:07:33,420
Stamford Raffles
arrived in Singapore in 1819

160
00:07:33,453 --> 00:07:36,524
with the British
East India Company,

161
00:07:36,557 --> 00:07:38,792
establishing it first
as a trading post

162
00:07:38,826 --> 00:07:40,127
for the British empire.

163
00:07:40,160 --> 00:07:43,997
♪

164
00:07:44,031 --> 00:07:46,366
Soon thereafter, Singapore grew,

165
00:07:46,399 --> 00:07:48,201
quickly becoming an economic hub

166
00:07:48,235 --> 00:07:50,538
and regional capital
for the British empire's

167
00:07:50,571 --> 00:07:53,541
new colony on
the Malay Peninsula.

168
00:07:53,574 --> 00:07:55,208
After World War II,

169
00:07:55,242 --> 00:07:57,277
Singapore clamored
for independence,

170
00:07:57,310 --> 00:07:59,780
first becoming a part
of the Malaysian Federation

171
00:07:59,813 --> 00:08:03,984
then a fully independent state
in 1965.

172
00:08:05,352 --> 00:08:07,855
Helmed by its first
prime minister, Lee Kuan Yew,

173
00:08:07,888 --> 00:08:11,725
tiny Singapore famously went
from a third-world outpost

174
00:08:11,759 --> 00:08:15,563
to a first-world nation
in a single generation.

175
00:08:18,732 --> 00:08:19,232
♪

176
00:08:26,273 --> 00:08:27,741
- In Singapore...
- Yep.

177
00:08:27,775 --> 00:08:30,077
Rules of negligence in
Singapore is very strict.

178
00:08:30,110 --> 00:08:31,879
We have to follow them.

179
00:08:31,912 --> 00:08:33,981
Like, I'm... I drive taxi.
Right.

180
00:08:34,014 --> 00:08:35,415
I can't break any law.

181
00:08:35,448 --> 00:08:36,850
So the camera catches you?

182
00:08:36,884 --> 00:08:38,085
Yeah, everything's in camera.

183
00:08:38,118 --> 00:08:39,486
It's very important everywhere.

184
00:08:39,519 --> 00:08:41,188
We have to follow the laws
of negligence.

185
00:08:41,221 --> 00:08:42,760
That's the reason Singapore
is very good.

186
00:08:42,790 --> 00:08:43,290
♪

187
00:08:46,927 --> 00:08:49,096
Singaporeans
are very hard-working persons.

188
00:08:49,129 --> 00:08:50,256
As human beings, what we need...

189
00:08:50,263 --> 00:08:51,832
Food to eat, clothes to wear,

190
00:08:51,865 --> 00:08:52,900
place to sleep.

191
00:08:52,933 --> 00:08:54,001
You can get in Singapore.

192
00:08:54,034 --> 00:08:55,202
So, in other words,

193
00:08:55,235 --> 00:08:56,770
we have to continue work.

194
00:08:56,804 --> 00:08:59,339
You working, you get something.
Once lazy, we're out.

195
00:08:59,372 --> 00:09:02,009
By some measures,
Singapore is a welfare state,

196
00:09:02,042 --> 00:09:03,877
taking care of the less
fortunate.

197
00:09:03,911 --> 00:09:06,546
But at its heart,
it's a cold-blooded meritocracy.

198
00:09:06,580 --> 00:09:08,849
You follow the rules
(and there are many),

199
00:09:08,882 --> 00:09:11,418
work hard, and you will
have a good life.

200
00:09:11,451 --> 00:09:13,020
That's the message.

201
00:09:13,053 --> 00:09:13,553
♪

202
00:09:18,759 --> 00:09:21,895
We are starting to define
the definition of success.

203
00:09:21,929 --> 00:09:24,898
I mean, before, we are very
clear with the five C's:

204
00:09:24,932 --> 00:09:27,935
car, condominium, a credit card,

205
00:09:27,968 --> 00:09:30,403
uh, cash, and career.

206
00:09:30,437 --> 00:09:32,305
Wow, that sounds awful, dude.

207
00:09:32,339 --> 00:09:33,974
- Yeah, dude.
- I mean...

208
00:09:34,007 --> 00:09:35,501
I grew up in that idea.
I grew up in...

209
00:09:35,508 --> 00:09:37,310
- That's not good.
- Yeah, exactly.

210
00:09:37,344 --> 00:09:39,112
It sounds kind of depressing.

211
00:09:39,146 --> 00:09:40,981
I know, but that's...
That's the past, I think.

212
00:09:41,014 --> 00:09:45,719
The Muslim quarter, just
following afternoon prayers.

213
00:09:45,753 --> 00:09:47,721
I'm here with Najip Ali,

214
00:09:47,755 --> 00:09:50,624
the Singaporean-Malay
entertainer and producer.

215
00:09:50,658 --> 00:09:53,093
Ah, okay.

216
00:09:53,126 --> 00:09:55,963
- Oh, looking good.
- This is it.

217
00:09:55,996 --> 00:09:58,165
- So this is...
- Lontong.

218
00:09:58,198 --> 00:09:59,592
- Lontong. And this...
- This is mee siam.

219
00:09:59,599 --> 00:10:01,534
Wow.
We're having lontong:

220
00:10:05,673 --> 00:10:11,011
rice cake, coconut gravy,
vegetables and a hardboiled egg.

221
00:10:11,044 --> 00:10:13,580
And mee siam: fried rice noodles

222
00:10:13,613 --> 00:10:15,683
with chili paste, prawns,
bean sprouts,

223
00:10:15,716 --> 00:10:17,951
and a spicy,
sweet-and-sour gravy,

224
00:10:17,985 --> 00:10:20,387
fried bean curd, and an egg.

225
00:10:22,890 --> 00:10:26,694
- Mmm.
- Delicious.

226
00:10:26,727 --> 00:10:29,296
I mean, we like to make fun
of Singapore in the West...

227
00:10:29,329 --> 00:10:31,098
Call it Disneyland with
the death penalty.

228
00:10:31,131 --> 00:10:34,768
And we're... we're skeptical,
of course, of one-party rule.

229
00:10:34,802 --> 00:10:38,338
We're skeptical of constraints
on freedom of the press

230
00:10:38,371 --> 00:10:41,441
or with the things you...
Can't do.

231
00:10:41,474 --> 00:10:44,277
- Can't do.
- Yeah, you can't, yeah.

232
00:10:44,311 --> 00:10:46,646
Do you think that young,
creative Singaporeans

233
00:10:46,680 --> 00:10:49,817
feel those constraints
and suffer from them?

234
00:10:49,850 --> 00:10:52,519
I think some of them
who travel knows better.

235
00:10:52,552 --> 00:10:55,689
Most of them are overeducated
and under-exposed,

236
00:10:55,723 --> 00:10:57,725
meaning they are... they have
very little experience

237
00:10:57,758 --> 00:10:59,126
in what they know.

238
00:10:59,159 --> 00:11:00,420
And I think that's
what we are lacking.

239
00:11:00,427 --> 00:11:02,029
They are looking
for things to do.

240
00:11:02,062 --> 00:11:04,231
And the problem with this
is always that we're living

241
00:11:04,264 --> 00:11:06,700
in a small country,
and we have nowhere to go

242
00:11:06,734 --> 00:11:08,535
and where to experience
these things.

243
00:11:08,568 --> 00:11:10,904
If you're in New York and you
don't like the city life,

244
00:11:10,938 --> 00:11:12,498
you say, "Shit, I'm..."
You say, "I'm not gonna..."

245
00:11:12,505 --> 00:11:13,807
You can say "shit" on the show.

246
00:11:13,841 --> 00:11:15,308
I'm gonna say this.

247
00:11:15,342 --> 00:11:16,602
I think we have two more
on this hour.

248
00:11:16,609 --> 00:11:18,145
That was one.

249
00:11:18,178 --> 00:11:19,539
"I'm going to get
out of the city."

250
00:11:19,546 --> 00:11:21,148
So you go to Minnesota,
you go to Texas.

251
00:11:21,181 --> 00:11:22,682
- Right.
- You take time to think about.

252
00:11:22,716 --> 00:11:24,610
And even in Malaysia, when you
are in Kuala Lumpur,

253
00:11:24,617 --> 00:11:26,847
and you go to, like... you go to
Terengganu, you go to Kuantan.

254
00:11:26,854 --> 00:11:28,889
We have nowhere to go.

255
00:11:31,591 --> 00:11:33,927
Not only is Singapore
a small city-state

256
00:11:33,961 --> 00:11:37,064
a little more than half
the size of LA,

257
